### PHP PDO Prepared Statements

Prepared statements protect against SQL injection by separating SQL logic from data.

### Why Prepared Statements?

```php
<?php
// DANGEROUS: SQL injection vulnerability
$sql = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = '" . $_POST["email"] . "'";

// SAFE: Using prepared statement
$stmt = $pdo->prepare("SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = :email");
$stmt->execute(["email" => $_POST["email"]]);
?>
```

### Named Parameters

```php
<?php
$sql = "INSERT INTO users (name, email, age) VALUES (:name, :email, :age)";
$stmt = $pdo->prepare($sql);

$stmt->execute([
    ":name" => "John",
    ":email" => "john@example.com",
    ":age" => 30
]);
?>
```

### Positional Parameters (Question Marks)

```php
<?php
$sql = "INSERT INTO users (name, email) VALUES (?, ?)";
$stmt = $pdo->prepare($sql);

$stmt->execute(["Jane", "jane@example.com"]);
?>
```

### Fetching Results

```php
<?php
// Single row
$stmt = $pdo->prepare("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?");
$stmt->execute([$id]);
$user = $stmt->fetch(); // Single row

// Multiple rows
$stmt = $pdo->prepare("SELECT * FROM users WHERE age > ?");
$stmt->execute([18]);
$users = $stmt->fetchAll(); // All matching rows

// Column count
$count = $stmt->rowCount();
?>
```

### Insert with Last Insert ID

```php
<?php
$stmt = $pdo->prepare("INSERT INTO users (name) VALUES (?)");
$stmt->execute(["Alice"]);

$lastId = $pdo->lastInsertId();
echo "New user ID: $lastId";
?>
```

### Benefits

| Benefit | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Security | Prevents SQL injection |
| Performance | SQL parsed once, executed multiple times |
| Maintainability | Cleaner code with named parameters |
| Portability | Works across all PDO-supported databases |

> **Key Point:** Always use prepared statements when accepting user input in SQL queries. Never concatenate or interpolate user data directly into SQL strings.
